Hit Probabilities & Valuing Hitters¶

In this installment of baseball research, I'm going to try fitting some different machine learning algorithms to predict the outcome of a batted ball based on things like its speed and trajectory. I'll test their accuracy and ultimately settle on a most effective model.

Modern Player Evaluation¶

A big part of modern baseball player evaluation is measuring players on things they have control over instead of on overall outcomes. When a hitter is up to the plate, one of the biggest things he's responsible for is hitting the ball hard and at a favorable trajectory. From the hitter's point of view, the outcome of a play can be affected by luck -- like a particularly talented fielder turning a likely hit into an out, or wind pushing routine flyout over the fence. If we strip these things out, it should be possible to uncover a hitter's true talent.

I'm going to use a hitter's batted-ball data to try to uncover their true talent. That is, trying to predict what should have happened based only on the hitter's contributions -- how hard they hit the ball and where.

Model Building¶

My goal here isn't necessarily to predict the outcome of a hit as accurately as possible. I'm intentionally leaving out features that would provide context, like the stadium, the fielding team, or the relevant fielder, because the batter has no control over them. I'll try a more descriptive model in another writeup.

If I'm trying to uncover a hitter's true talent, I'll build models using only the things the hitter is responsible for:

  • batted ball speed
  • batted ball vertical angle (launch angle)
  • batted ball horizontal angle (direction/spray angle)
  • batter handedness

As far as the models themselves go, I mostly care about the probabilistic predictions from each model. I can get the outcome classification from that data, but more importantly, those probabilities are useful. If we assign a value to the results of a batted ball, we can calculate the expected value of the batted ball and use that to value a hitter.

Before I start fitting any models, I actually need to calculate the batted ball horizontal angle myself. I'm using data that I previously calibrated to remove any stadium measurement bias (writeup here).

Calculating horizontal launch angle¶

Statcast directly provides the batted ball speed and vertical launch angle, but doesn't exactly give the horizontal launch angle. What it does give is the hc_x and hc_y, which correspond to the x and y coordinate positions where the ball either landed or was fielded. This doesn't exactly give the horizontal angle at which the ball was batted, since wind or ball spin can change the trajectory of the ball mid-air, but it should be pretty close. Let's check out what that data looks like.

Huh. So, it turns out hc_x and hc_y aren't centered with (0,0) at home plate, nor are they in units of feet. I dug around a little, and according to this document, they're defined as

Coordinates entered by operator in pressbox of where the ball is fielded. Based on 250x250 field graphic, where 0,0 is in the upper left corner, in very deep left field, and 250,250 is in the lower right corner, in foul territory between 1B and home plate. The fields are centered in that space, the x=125 axis runs through the middle of 2B, the pitchers mound and home plate; the 1B and 3B bases are roughly aligned on the y=175 line.

Ok, fine. So I'll put it into a normal coordinate system. The x-coordinate is easy enough to transform, I'll just subtract 125 from each entry. For the y-coordinate, I'll filter to balls hit straight up the middle of the field (x=125), where the batted ball distance should be equal to the y-coordinate distance. If I fit a linear regression between the hit distance and the y-coordinate for balls where x=125, then I'll be able to zero-out the y coordinate and get the transformation from pixel units to feet!

One thing to check -- The document above says hit_distance_sc measures the distance traveled by the ball, and hc_x and hc_y measure distance until the ball was fielded. On groundballs, hit_distance_sc might report a distance right in front of home plate and hc_x and hc_y might report a distance somewhere in the infield.

I'll just plot hc_y against hit_distance_sc with the hit type and see what's what.

Yep, so that's actually a problem. Ground balls and some line drives have further registered distances by hc_y (it's confusing, lower numbers are further) than the hit_distance_sc. All this means is that I'll just filter out ground balls and line drives when I regress hc_y and hit_distance_sc.

In [21]:
df_adj = df.copy(deep=True)

# zero hc_x
df_adj['hc_x'] = df_adj.hc_x - 125

# get non ground-balls and line-drives hit up the middle
df_0 = df_adj[(df_adj.hc_x >= -1) &
              (df_adj.hc_x <= 1) &
              (df_adj.bb_type != 'ground_ball') &
              (df_adj.bb_type != 'line_drive')]

df_0 = df_0.dropna(subset=['hit_distance_sc']).reset_index(drop=True)

X = df_0[['hit_distance_sc']]
y = df_0['hc_y']

y_mod = LinearRegression().fit(X, y)

print('y-coord translation = %0.3f' % y_mod.intercept_)
print('pixel-feet conversion factor = %0.3f' % y_mod.coef_[0])

# transform y-coords so home plate is at y=0 and larger = further
df_adj['hc_y'] = (-1 * df_adj['hc_y']) + y_mod.intercept_

# apply conversion from pixels to feet
df_adj['hc_x'] = df_adj['hc_x'] / abs(y_mod.coef_[0])
df_adj['hc_y'] = df_adj['hc_y'] / abs(y_mod.coef_[0])

# calculate the horizontal angle based on hc_x and hc_y
direction = []
for i in range(len(df_adj)):
    hcx = df_adj.hc_x.iloc[i]
    hcy = df_adj.hc_y.iloc[i]

    if (hcx >= 0 and hcy >= 0) | (hcx < 0 and hcy >= 0):
        dr = np.rad2deg(np.arctan(hcx / hcy))

    elif hcx >= 0 and hcy < 0:
        dr = np.rad2deg(np.arctan(abs(hcx / hcy))) + 90

    elif hcx < 0 and hcy < 0:
        dr = -np.rad2deg(np.arctan(hcx / hcy)) - 90

    else:
        dr = np.nan

    direction.append(dr)

df_adj['direction'] = direction

y-coord translation = 212.726
pixel-feet conversion factor = -0.452

Looking back at the first plot, this passes the eye test. The y-coord translation means home plate is located at about y=213, which matches up with that plot. I'll divide hc_x and hc_y by 0.45 to convert to feet.

Let's remake that first plot to make sure we've successfully transformed the data, and I'll add another plot to make sure the direction angle makes sense.

Predicting outcomes¶

I don't need a whole lot of information for these models: the four features I mentioned above, plus the outcome of the play. There's a few adjustments we need to make:

1) Remove any bunts from the dataset
2) map non-hit outcomes to 'out' (Statcast elaborates on the out type, e.g. sacrifice fly, fielders choice)
3) One-hot encode batter handedness
4) Over-sample imbalanced data

In [9]:
# stand = handedness
cols = ['events', 'stand', 'launch_speed', 'launch_angle', 'direction']

df_mod = df_adj[cols]

# 1) drop bunts
df_mod = df_mod[~df_mod['events'].isin(['sac_bunt', 'sac_bunt_double_play'])]

# 2) anything that's not a hit = out
df_mod.loc[~df_mod['events'].isin(
    ['single', 'double', 'triple', 'home_run']), 'events'] = 'out'

# 3) one-hot encode handedness
df_mod = pd.concat([df_mod, pd.get_dummies(df_mod.stand)], axis=1)

# drop unecessary columns & rename to be a little clearer
df_mod = df_mod.drop(columns=['stand', 'L'])
df_mod = df_mod.rename(columns={'R': 'is_Right'})

Looking at the distribution of outcomes, it's pretty clear that we need to do something to balance the data. Outs are 3x as common as the next most frequent outcome. Imbalanced data like this can make it hard for our models to be able to recognize patterns that describe a minority class. I'm going to use SMOTE (synthetic minority oversampling technique) to balance the dataset, using the imblearn package.

Here's what SMOTE does to a sample of data.

In [11]:
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE

s = df_mod.sample(n=20000).reset_index(drop=True)

X = s[['launch_speed', 'launch_angle', 'direction', 'is_Right']]
y = s['events']

# perform resampling
sm = SMOTE()
X, y = sm.fit_resample(X, y)

print('Total oversampled data: %s' % len(y))

Total oversampled data: 66765

I'm going to rely on the imblearn package again to set up a pipeline for cross-validating the models. If I'm going to oversample the data, it's important that I train on the oversampled data and then validate/test on the standard data. imblearn's pipeline is set up to apply oversampling just to the training data and then validate/test on the unsampled data.

I've settled on these 6 popular classifiers:

  • logistic regression
  • k-nearest neighbors
  • support vector machine
  • decision tree
  • random forest
  • gradient boosting

And I'm going to use 5 metrics to evaluate the models, which together should give a good picture of the best overall model:

  • F1 score (weighted by instances of each label)
  • recall (weighted by label)
  • precision (weighted by label)
  • balanced accuracy (for imbalanced datasets)
  • log loss

For this exercise, I'm going to use mostly default settings for the classifiers, as well as a pared down sample size of 20,000 points (this will increase with SMOTE). Once I pick the best model, I'll do some parameter tuning in another writeup.

In [14]:
from imblearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_validate
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score, accuracy_score, log_loss, precision_score, recall_score, make_scorer

from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier, GradientBoostingClassifier

# scoring metrics
scoring = {
    'f1_weighted': 'f1_weighted',
    'accuracy': 'balanced_accuracy',
    'recall': make_scorer(recall_score, average='weighted'),
    'precision': make_scorer(precision_score, average='weighted', zero_division=0),
    'neg_log_loss': 'neg_log_loss'
    }

# define classifier models
classifiers = [
    LogisticRegression(multi_class='multinomial'),
    KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=50),
    SVC(probability=True),
    DecisionTreeClassifier(),
    RandomForestClassifier(),
    GradientBoostingClassifier()
    ]

# classifier names
clf_names = [
    'Logistic Regression',
    'KNN',
    'SVM',
    'Decision Tree',
    'Random Forest',
    'Gradient Boosting'
    ]

# use sample so this doesn't take forever
s = df_mod.sample(n=20000).reset_index(drop=True)

# scale and center numeric columns
to_scale = ['launch_speed', 'launch_angle', 'direction']
s[to_scale] = StandardScaler().fit_transform(s[to_scale])

X = s[['launch_speed', 'launch_angle', 'direction', 'is_Right']]
y = s['events']

f1, acc, recall, precision, log_loss = [], [], [], [], []
for clf, clf_nm in zip(classifiers, clf_names):
    
    # setup pipeline to oversample, then fit model
    pipe = Pipeline([
        ('smote', SMOTE()),
        ('classify', clf)
        ])

    # cross-validate 5 times
    res = cross_validate(pipe, X, y, cv=5, scoring=scoring)
    results = pd.DataFrame(res)

    total_time = (sum(results.fit_time) + sum(results.score_time)) / 60
    print('Time to cross-validate %s = %0.3f min.' % (clf_nm, total_time))

    # save average scores
    f1.append(np.mean(results.test_f1_weighted))
    acc.append(np.mean(results.test_accuracy))
    recall.append(np.mean(results.test_recall))
    precision.append(np.mean(results.test_precision))
    log_loss.append(np.mean(results.test_neg_log_loss))

eval_cols = [
    'models',
    'F1 Score',
    'Balanced Accuracy',
    'Recall',
    'Precision',
    'Neg Log Loss'
    ]

model_eval = pd.DataFrame(data=zip(clf_names, f1, acc, recall, precision, log_loss),
                          columns=eval_cols)

display(model_eval)

In the final shootout, the gradient boosting algorithm was the best in most metrics. The SVM was also quite good, but slightly worse across the board and easily the slowest model to fit (related to forcing probabilistic output).

With that, it looks like the gradient boosting model is the way to go. I have a few follow-ups to this reports I'd like to do:
